Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Halve, peel, and finely chop
@yellow onion{1}(halved, peeled, and finely chopped). Mince or grate @garlic{4%cloves}(minced).
Thinly slice @scallions{4}(thinly sliced).

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over high heat. Add
@ground beef{12%ounce} and break up into pieces with a #spatula{} or #wooden spoon{}.
Cook until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir in @Mexican spice blend{1%tablespoon} and
season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove from pan and set aside.

Add onions, garlic, and a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp} to same pan over medium heat.
Cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir in 2 tsp @southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon}
and half the scallions. Cook until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}. Stir in
@diced tomatoes{2%can} and ground beef. Season with salt and pepper.

Place a layer of filling in a small #baking dish{} (ours is 11 x 7). Top with 2
@flour tortillas{6} (tearing to fit). Add a layer of @Monterey Jack cheese{1%cup}.
Repeat with three more layers, finishing with a layer of filling and cheese.

> TIP: It's OK if tortillas don't cover filling completely.

Bake casserole until melted and bubbling, ~{5-7%minutes}.

> TIP: For a golden and crispy top, heat broiler to high and broil casserole a
> further 2-3 minutes.

Meanwhile, halve @lime{1}(halved). Halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce}(halved). Toss
@mixed greens{6%ounce} and grape tomatoes in a large #bowl{} with a squeeze of lime
and a drizzle of olive oil. Season with salt and pepper.

Sprinkle casserole with remaining scallions. Cut casserole into slices and serve
with salad and a dollop of @sour cream{8%tablespoon} on the side.

> If you have time, let casserole rest a few minutes for cleaner slices.